          "level": 3,
          "parentId": null,
          "content": "<p>Syntopicon Fourteen opens with the Prophet Jacob, who is also known as Israel, and the genesis of his twelve sons—the Children of Israel. The story of Jacob completes our introduction of the four Patriarchs—Abraham, Ishmael, Isaac, and Jacob—all of whom lived during the Middle Bronze Age in the lands of Greater Syria and Palestine.  The Middle Bronze Age may be roughly dated  as the six hundred year period between  2100 BCE until 1500 BCE. It was followed by the Late Bronze Age, which extended approximately three centuries from about 1500 BCE until 1200 BCE, when the art of smelting iron began to take hold in the Near East. In Greater Syria and Palestine, the first People known to have mastered the difficult and dangerous art of iron smelting—which required extremely hot furnaces—were the Philistines of Palestine’s Southern Mediterranean coast. </p><p>     By about 2000 BCE, Canaanite Civilization—the genius of which was Lebanese—had already begun to flourish in the villages and towns of the Lebanese coast. As we will see in Syntopicon Fifteen, the Greeks called Lebanon “Phoenicia” and its Canaanite People the “Phoenicians” because of the high-quality purple dies they produced from sea snails. The Greek name “<em>Phoinίkios, Φοινιkίoς</em>” is an exonym and literally means “the Purple People,” from the Greek word “<em>phoínix</em>,<em> φοίνιξ</em>,” which means “purple.” The Ancient Phoenicians of Lebanon did not call themselves “Phoenicians,” but rather “Canaanites,” which was their standard endonym. Indeed, the Lebanese “Phoenicians”  were, in fact, <em>the </em>Canaanites—especially in the context of the wider world of commerce, trade, and international markets. Linguistically, “Phoenician” —the tongue of the Canaanites of Lebanon—differed very little from both their Hebrew speaking neighbors and the more Southerly Canaanites, such as the Peoples of Sodom and Gomorrah on the shores of today’s Dead Sea. These Canaanite vernaculars may therefore be regarded as dialects of a single linguistic family. For this reason, the Prophet Isaiah rightly refers to Hebrew as “the language of Canaan” (Isaiah, 19:18).</p><p>    From the Prophet Jacob to King Saul, the figures discussed in the first chapters of Syntopicon Fourteen belong to the Middle and Late Bronze Ages. As just indicated, the safe and successful smelting of iron around 1200 BCE ushered in the Iron Age in the Near East. It must be noted, however, that Human Beings had long been able to work iron before they learned to smelt it. Indeed, the skills of iron working go back to prehistoric times and the earliest Prophets. In those early times, however, the iron that they crafted was harvested from meteors and not produced in smelting furnaces. As we will see, in our discussion of the Prophet David, this meteoric origin explains why iron was often called “the heavenly metal.” Even so, the earliest technologies of iron smelting began to proliferate in the Near East as early as the time of the Prophet Moses and the Israelite Invasion of the Promised Land, which probably occurred during the thirteenth century BCE. Formally speaking, however, the beginning of the Iron Age  and the end of the Middle Eastern Late Bronze Age for the Children of Israel  coincides withthe reign King Saul (<em>Ṭālūt</em>), who shrewdly appropriated the technology of iron smelting from the Philistines and introduced it among the Children of Israel. This move would  deprive the Philistines of the military advantage provided by their indigenously produced iron weapons. Naturally, the Prophet-Kings David and Solomon, who immediately succeeded the reign of King Saul, constitute Early Iron Age figures, and it is with them that Syntopicon Fourteen ends. All of the remaining Prophets treated in Syntopicons Fifteen and Sixteen belong clearly to the Iron Age. In <em>The First Teaching</em>, this period also serves as a chief marker of the End of Time, as will be discussed more fully in the present Syntopicon. In the days of the Prophet David—roughly one thousand years before the birth of Jesus Christ—the Iron Age was still very young, and it would continue until our present Age of Plastics and Electricity, both of which require the massive production of high-quality iron and steel in order to function. <a href=\"/v/14/late-bronze-age-messengers-their-times/web-extension\" class=\"web-extension-chip\" data-web-extension-link=\"true\" aria-label=\"Open web extension 1\">Web-Extension 1</a></p>",
