              "displayNumber": 37,
              "markerKey": "book-twenty-three-god-s-messenger-king-solomon-sulayman-his-unique-prophetic-powers-his-temple-his-reign:syntopicon:37",
              "origin": "syntopicon",
              "content": "<p> We have introduced the Cooper, Bronze, and Iron Ages as broad-ranging dating structures based on the prehistorical and ancient development of technologies of metal production. The expression “Golden Age,” however, is mythological and is taken from widespread prehistoric and ancient beliefs about humanity’s past and its progressive ages of degeneration. Before the appearance of the modern West over the last four centuries with its radically different notion of progress based on powerful new technologies, such constructions of earlier mythological ages constituted a dominant view of human beings about themselves in many of the world’s cultures, although these overlapping pictures contained significant differences. Among the Greeks, for example, from whom, in the West, we have taken our notion of the “Golden Age,” it was portrayed as the greatest of all times. The Golden Age was a time of great abundance, unbroken happiness, perfect peace, and long life, when death would come to people like a pleasant sleep after centuries and centuries of a rewarding lifetimes. In the Greek view, human beings of the Golden Age were transformed after death into “the good spirits,” who lived above the earth and became the guardians and helpers of later generations of human beings. The Greeks believed that humankind was vegetarian during the Golden Age. They lived exclusively by agrarian cultivation, and there were no ships on the seas or international trade. In later Western thought, especially among the Early Moderns, the Greek notion of the Golden Age became the foundation of several utopian philosophies, which sought to regain the lost goodness of the Golden Age. Their experiments in thought also underlie the rise of democratic, socialist, and communist ideologies in the West.</p><p>    In Ancient Greek thought, as the Golden Age declined, it changed into “the Silver Age,” which was greatly inferior to the Golden Age that preceded it. The Silver Age was the first age of human folly. Fighting and war broke out, and human beings began to kill and oppress each other. Moreover, they altered their pristine form of worship, which they had held to in the Golden Age, and refused to worship correctly as they had been accustomed to do before. Thus, “the gods” put them away at a distance out of anger. There was brutishness and much violence. The spirits of the dead in the Silver Age, according to Greek myth, became good spirits but were subterranean.</p><p>    The Bronze Age followed the Silver Age. The Bronze Age was also known as the Brazen Age. Human beings became powerful and terrible, lovers of violence and war. It was a time of organized brutality and deliberately premeditated cruelty. They fashioned bronze and made their weapons and houses of it. Human beings made knives and swords. They slaughtered cattle and ate meat for food. They fell in death at each other’s hands. When they died, they went to the subterranean realm of shadows called Hades, where they abided without names or honor. Not all the human beings of the Bronze Age, however, were evil. Rather, there were also the “heroes of old” who arose to defend the people and protect them from harm such as the ancient heroes of Troy and Thebes. When they died, the heroic spirits went westward to the Islands of the Blessed.</p><p>    In this framework, the Bronze Age was followed by the Iron Age, when iron tools and weapons replaced those of bronze. Goodness, justice, and piety were no longer regarded as being of value. Crimes of every sort and description spread among human beings. There was no rest from toil or labor, and people’s lives were filled with sorrow and hard work by day and by night. The “gods” became angry with human beings and put burdens upon them that were even more bitter. Fathers strove against sons. Sons strove against fathers. Brothers ceased to love each other. Friends turned against one another. Even the guest fought with his host. </p>",
